---
import Container from '../components/Container.astro';
import FadeUp from '../components/FadeUp';
---

<section class="py-20 lg:py-28 bg-pure-cream">
  <Container>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-12 lg:gap-20 items-center">
      <div>
        <FadeUp client:visible delay={0.2}>
          <div class="aspect-[4/5] rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-soft-cream">
            <img
              src="/images/origin.svg"
              alt="Chef preparing Thai dishes in the kitchen"
              class="w-full h-full object-cover"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
        </FadeUp>
      </div>
      <div>
        <FadeUp client:visible>
          <span class="inline-block text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-thai-chili-red mb-3">The Origin</span>
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-semibold text-deep-indigo leading-tight">
            Why small bowls?
          </h2>
          <div class="mt-6 space-y-4 text-dusty-slate leading-relaxed max-w-lg">
            <p>
              Buriram opened in 2024 with a simple idea: Thai food is too good to only eat one dish at a time. But big plates mean big commitment.
            </p>
            <p>
              The small-bowl concept came from Chinese dim sum culture — order many, share everything, taste it all. We applied that to Thai flavors, and something clicked.
            </p>
            <p>
              Our recipes come from family kitchens in Buriram province, passed down and adapted for Kuala Lumpur palates. The heat is real. The portions are honest. The bowls are small on purpose.
            </p>
          </div>
        </FadeUp>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Container>
</section>
